(1266, 1, '2018-12-03 06:13:27', '2018-12-03 06:13:27', 'The advent of refrigerators has indeed been a boon. The joys of an iced drink aside, crucially it helps us preserve food for long periods. But there are places where this modern convenience is still a distant dream.\r\n\r\nSo a system that can keep food and medications cool in remote, hot locations, operate without electricity or fuel, is a certain life safer.\r\n\r\nWell, guess what! A group of scientists from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the US have invented a set-up, using “commonly available low-cost materials” that can do precisely that.\r\n\r\nHow does the device work?\r\n\r\nSince ancient times it has been known that things can be cooled at night or in the shade – away from sunlight.\r\n<h4>This cooling happens because heat is radiated out at mid-infrared wavelengths, and the Earth’s atmosphere does not stop these emissions. The emissions shoot out into outer space unimpeded—a natural phenomenon. This leads to a draining of heat—and hence, the cooling.</h4>\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_1232\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"1200\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-1232\" src=\"http://localhost/wordbetterpre/wp-content/uploads/2018/12/u7.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1200\" height=\"628\" /> Rain clouds hovering over Mumbai’s Bandra-Worli sea link[/caption]\r\n\r\nfelis tellus mollis orci, sed rhoncus pronin sapien nunc accuan eget. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Sed viverra ornare feugiat. Cras condimentum viverra ante, nec bibendum dui scelerisque venenatis. Fusce mollis ut lectus a pulvinar. Morbi eget nunc lobortis, congue eros id, dapibus tellus. Nulla a efficitur eros. Phasellus nisl augue, fermentum id nunc a, lobortis pulvinar enim. Nunc non commodo magna. Proin non sem augue. Donec quis velit luctus, mattis elit sit amet, laoreet dolor.\r\n\r\nNam facilisis congue iaculis. Suspendisse pellentesque mauris justo, sit amet tristique erat ullamcorper quis. Duis eros